Stock symbol GWSO, yesterday I mentioned I would be posting this company today at 6:30am. Kevin Harrington from the show shark tank is just now announcing he is a part of this company and this stock and company should do very well. @globalwarmingresolution 👍

node.text:
Celebrate with @unworldoceansday and @oceanic.global starting today at 10 am EST. 
When the world feels like
it’s at a standstill, it’s important to remember what keeps it spinning. Our ocean is our life source, supporting us & every other organism on earth. Celebrate @UNWorldOceansDay
on June 8th with @UnitedNations
and @Oceanic.Global
to learn what thought leaders around the world are doing to protect the ocean and how you can be part of the solution. Featured ocean voices include @caradelevingne,
@fatoumata_diawara__, @fcousteau, @c.syresmith, @jackharries, @thegreatbubblebarrier, @codysimpson, @oceanx, @alessandraambrosio and
more! 
This all-digital event is
free and open to all online. Learn more & register:  UNWorldOceansDay.org/2020

node.text:
Tiny @underwater hands 🖐!!
Aka Polyps Coral.
Coral polyps are tiny, soft-bodied organisms related to sea anemones and jellyfish. At their base is a hard, protective limestone skeleton called a calicle, which forms the structure of coral reefs. Reefs begin when a polyp attaches itself to a rock on the sea floor, then divides, or buds, into thousands of clones.
🎥 @scubahai_nz
#ocean #sea #coral

node.text:
Did you know that Octopuses have 3 hearts, 9 brains and blue blood? 🐙🤯
-
Why does an octopus have 9 brains?

Octopuses have 9 brains because, in addition to the central brain, each of 8 arms has a mini-brain that allows it to act independently.
.
What’s a crazy sea fact you know? Let us know in the comments ⬇️
📸: @xbeiro
#DiscoverOcean #octopus #nature #facts

The Pufferfish was thrilled, a spacious new home with ocean views & lived happily ever after... 😁”
#DiscoverOcean

Southern Blue Ringed Octopus (Hapalochlaena maculosa) have an elaborate nervous system connected to chromatophores that change the colour of their skin within milliseconds. This is an example of aposematic colouration in which this animal communicates a warning signal to predators, indicating their venomous potential. They are just such spectacular animals! 🐙
